1221: EAD4         ;---------------------------- Open File - F (15) ---------------------------;
1222: EAD4         ;  This function opens a specified file for reading or writing. The FCB,    ;
1223: EAD4         ; whose address must be in register DE, tells CP/M the user number,         ;
1224: EAD4         ; the logical disk, the file name, and the file type. All other bytes of    ;
1225: EAD4         ; the FCB will normally be set to O.                                        ;
1226: EAD4         ;  The code returned by the BDOS in register A indicates whether the file   ;
1227: EAD4         ; has been opened successfully. If A contains OFFH, then the BOOS was       ;
1228: EAD4         ; unable to find the correct entry in the directory. If A= 0,1,2, or 3,     ;
1229: EAD4         ; then the file has been opened.                                            ;
1230: EAD4         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 0FH                                    ;
1231: EAD4         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1232: EAD4         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1233: EAD4         ;																			;
1234: EAD4         ;---------------------------- Open File - F (15) ---------------------------;
1235: EAD4             vOpenFile:
1236: EAD4 CD BE EF               CALL   InitializeExtentNumberMSB ; Clear the Extent number
1237: EAD7 CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; do we need to reselect disk?
1238: EADA C3 F4 ED               JP     OpenFile
1239: EADD
1240: EADD         ;---------------------------- Close File - 10 (16) -------------------------;
1241: EADD         ;  This function terminates the processing of a file to which you have      ;
1242: EADD         ; written information. Under CP/M you do not need to close a file that you  ;
1243: EADD         ; have been reading. However, if you ever intend for your program to        ;
1244: EADD         ; function correctly under MP/M (the multi-user version of CP/M) you        ;
1245: EADD         ; should close all files regardless of their use.                           ;
1246: EADD         ;  The Close File function, like Open File, returns a directory code in     ;
1247: EADD         ; the A register. Register A will contain OFFH if the BOOS could not        ;
1248: EADD         ; close the file successfully. If A is 0, 1, 2, or 3, then the file has     ;
1249: EADD         ; been closed.                                                              ;
1250: EADD         ;                                                                           ;
1251: EADD         ;  When the BDOS closes a file to which data has been written, it writes    ;
1252: EADD         ; the current contents of the FCB out to the disk directory, updating       ;
1253: EADD         ; an existing directory entry by matching the disk, name, type, and         ;
1254: EADD         ; extent number in the same manner that the Open File function does.        ;
1255: EADD         ; Note that the BDOS does not transfer the last record of the file to the   ;
1256: EADD         ; disk during the close operation. It merely updates the file directory.    ;
1257: EADD         ; You must arrange to flush any partly filled record to the disk. If the    ;
1258: EADD         ; file that you have created is a standard CP/M ASCII text file, you must   ;
1259: EADD         ; arrange to fill the unused portion of the record with the standard lAH    ;
1260: EADD         ; end-of-file characters as CP/M expects.                                   ;
1261: EADD         ;                                                                           ;
1262: EADD         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 10H                                    ;
1263: EADD         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1264: EADD         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1265: EADD         ;																			;
1266: EADD         ;---------------------------- Close File - 10 (16) -------------------------;
1267: EADD             vCloseFile:
1268: EADD CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk
1269: EAE0 C3 35 EE               JP     CloseDirEntry
1270: EAE3         ;---------------------Search for First Name Match - 11 (17) ----------------;
1271: EAE3         ;  This function scans down the file directory for the first entry that     ;
1272: EAE3         ; matches the file name, type, and extent in the FCB addressed by DE.       ;
1273: EAE3         ; The file name, type, and extent may contain a "?" (ASCII 3FH) in one or   ;
1274: EAE3         ; more character positions. Where a "?" occurs, the BDOS will match any     ;
1275: EAE3         ; character in the corresponding position in the file directory. This is    ;
1276: EAE3         ; known as ambiguous file name matching.                                    ;
1277: EAE3         ;  The first byte of an FCB normally contains the logical disk number code. ;
1278: EAE3         ; A value of 0 indicates the default disk, while 1 means disk A, 2 is B,    ;
1279: EAE3         ; and so on up to a possible maximum of 16 for disk P. However, if this     ;
1280: EAE3         ; byte contains a "?", the BDOS will search the default logical disk and    ;
1281: EAE3         ; will match the file name and type regardless of the user number. This     ;
1282: EAE3         ; function is normally used in conjunction with the Search Next function.   ;
1283: EAE3         ; Search First, in the process of matching a file, leaves certain           ;
1284: EAE3         ; variables in the BDOS set, ready for a subsequent Search Next.            ;
1285: EAE3         ;  Both Search First and Search Next return a directory code in the         ;
1286: EAE3         ; A register. With Search First, A = OFFH when no files match the FCB,      ;
1287: EAE3         ; if a file match is found, A will have a value of 0, I, 2, or 3.           ;
1288: EAE3         ;                                                                           ;
1289: EAE3         ;  To locate the particular directory entry that either the Search First    ;
1290: EAE3         ; or Search Next function matched, multiply the directory code returned     ;
1291: EAE3         ; in A by the length of a directory entry (32 bytes). This is easily done   ;
1292: EAE3         ; by adding the A register to itself five times. Then add the DMA address   ;
1293: EAE3         ; to get the actual address where the matched directory entry is stored.    ;
1294: EAE3         ;  There are many occasions when you may need to write a program that will  ;
1295: EAE3         ; accept an ambiguous file name and operate on all of the file names that   ;
1296: EAE3         ; match it. (The DIR and ERA commands built into the CCP are examples that  ;
1297: EAE3         ; use ambiguous file names.) To do this, you must use several BDOS          ;
1298: EAE3         ; functions: the Set DMA Address function (code 26), this function          ;
1299: EAE3         ; (Search First), and Search Next (code 18). All of this is shown in the    ;
1300: EAE3         ; subroutine given in Figure 5-17.                                          ;
1301: EAE3         ;                                                                           ;
1302: EAE3         ;                                                                           ;
1303: EAE3         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 11H                                    ;
1304: EAE3         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1305: EAE3         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1306: EAE3         ;																			;
1307: EAE3         ;---------------------Search for First Name Match - 11 (17) ----------------;
1308: EAE3             vFindFirst:
1309: EAE3 0E 00                  LD     C,0                  ; Length assuming '?' true
1310: EAE5 2A B4 EA               LD     HL,(paramDE)         ; Get the FCB
1311: EAE8 7E                     LD     A,(HL)               ; DIsk/User No
1312: EAE9 FE 3F                  CP     QMARK                ; Does it contain '?' ?
1313: EAEB 28 08                  JR     Z,QMarkFind          ;  if Yes, skip disk reselect
1314: EAED         ;  and reset of EXT
1315: EAED
1316: EAED CD BE EF               CALL   InitializeExtentNumberMSB ; Set Ext to 0
1317: EAF0 CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Use FCB to set currentDisk
1318: EAF3 0E 0F                  LD     C,nameLength         ; Match name,type and extent
1319: EAF5
1320: EAF5             QMarkFind:
1321: EAF5 CD F6 EF               CALL   SearchForDirectoryRecord ; Find the directory record
1322: EAF8 C3 15 F2               JP     CopyDirEntryToUserDMA ; Move it to the User's buffer
1323: EAFB
1324: EAFB         ;---------------------Search for Next Name Match - 12 (18) -----------------;
1325: EAFB         ;	This function searches down the file directory for the next file name,  ;
1326: EAFB         ; type, and extent that match the FCB specified in a previous Search First  ;
1327: EAFB         ; function call. Search First and Search Next are the only BDOS functions   ;
1328: EAFB         ; that must be used together. As you can see, the Search Next function      ;
1329: EAFB         ; does not require an FCB address as an input parameter-all the necessary   ;
1330: EAFB         ; information will have been left in the BDOS on the Search First call.     ;
1331: EAFB         ; Like Search First, Search Next returns a directory code in the A register,;
1332: EAFB         ; in this case, if A = OFFH, it means that there are no more files that     ;
1333: EAFB         ; match the file control block. If A is not OFFH, it will be a value of     ;
1334: EAFB         ; 0, 1, 2, or 3, indicating the relative directory entry number.            ;
1335: EAFB         ;                                                                           ;
1336: EAFB         ;  There are two ways of using the Search First/ Next calls. Consider a     ;
1337: EAFB         ; simple file copying program that takes as input an ambiguous file name.   ;
1338: EAFB         ; You could scan the file directory, matching all of the possible file      ;
1339: EAFB         ; names, possibly displaying them on the console, and storing the names of  ;
1340: EAFB         ; the files to be copied in a table inside your program. This would have    ;
1341: EAFB         ; the advantage of enabling you to present the file names to the operator   ;
1342: EAFB         ; before any copying occurred. You could even arrange for the operator to   ;
1343: EAFB         ; select which files to copy on a file-by-file basis. One disadvantage      ;
1344: EAFB         ; would be that you could not accurately predict how many files might be    ;
1345: EAFB         ; selected. On some hard disk systems you might have to accommodate several ;
1346: EAFB         ; thousand file names.                                                      ;
1347: EAFB         ;  The alternative way of handling the problem would be to match one file   ;
1348: EAFB         ; name, copy it, then match the next file name, copy it, and so on. If you  ;
1349: EAFB         ; gave the operator the choice of selecting which files to copy, this person;
1350: EAFB         ; would have to wait at the terminal as each file was being copied, but the ;
1351: EAFB         ; program would not need to have large table areas set aside to hold file   ;
1352: EAFB         ; names. This solution to the problem is slightly more complicated, as you  ;
1353: EAFB         ; can see from the logic in Figure 5-17.                                    ;
1354: EAFB         ;  The subroutine in Figure 5-17, Get Next File (GNF), contains all of the  ;
1355: EAFB         ; necessary logic to search down a directory for both alternatives described;
1356: EAFB         ; It does require that you indicate on entry whether it should search for   ;
1357: EAFB         ; the first or next file match, by setting A to zero or some nonzero value  ;
1358: EAFB         ; respectively.                                                             ;
1359: EAFB         ;  You can see from Figure 5-17 that whenever the subroutine is called to   ;
1360: EAFB         ; get the next file, you must execute a Search First function to re-find    ;
1361: EAFB         ; the  previous file. Only then can a Search Next be issued. As with all    ;
1362: EAFB         ; functions that return a directory code in A, if this value is not OFFH, it;
1363: EAFB         ; will be the relative directory entry number in the directory record       ;
1364: EAFB         ; currently in memory. This directory record will have been read into memory;
1365: EAFB         ; at whatever address was specified at the last Set DMA Address function    ;
1366: EAFB         ; call. Notwithstanding its odd name, the DMA Address is simply the address ;
1367: EAFB         ; into which any record input from disk will be placed. If the Set DMA      ;
1368: EAFB         ; Address function has not been used to change the value, then the CP/M     ;
1369: EAFB         ; default DMA address, location 0080H, will be used to hold the directory   ;
1370: EAFB         ; record.                                                                   ;
1371: EAFB         ;  The actual code for locating the address of the particular directory     ;
1372: EAFB         ;  entry matched by the Search First/ Next functions is shown in Figure 5-17;
1373: EAFB         ;  near the label GNFC. The method involves multiplying the directory code  ;
1374: EAFB         ;  by 32 and then adding this product to the current DMA address.	        ;
1375: EAFB         ;                                                                           ;
1376: EAFB         ;                                                                           ;
1377: EAFB         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 12H                                    ;
1378: EAFB         ;			Entry Parameters:	None , Assume previous Search First Call	;
1379: EAFB         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1380: EAFB         ;																			;
1381: EAFB         ;---------------------Search for Next Name Match - 12 (18) -----------------;
1382: EAFB             vFindNext:
1383: EAFB 2A B6 F4               LD     HL,(searchAddress)   ; Get Current Dir Entry
1384: EAFE 22 B4 EA               LD     (paramDE),HL         ; Get the user's FCB
1385: EB01 CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Reselect if needed
1386: EB04 CD 0B F0               CALL   GetNextDirectoryRecord ; Go find the next directory record
1387: EB07 C3 15 F2               JP     CopyDirEntryToUserDMA ; Copy directory entry to user
1388: EB0A
1389: EB0A         ;--------------------------------Delete File - 13 (19) ---------------------;
1390: EB0A         ; This function logically deletes from the file directory files that match  ;
1391: EB0A         ; the FCB addressed by DE. It does so by replacing the first byte of each   ;
1392: EB0A         ; relevant directory entry (remember, a single file can have several        ;
1393: EB0A         ; entries, one for each extent) by the value OE5H. This flags the directory ;
1394: EB0A         ; entry as being available for use.                                         ;
1395: EB0A         ;                                                                           ;
1396: EB0A         ;  Like the previous two functions, Search First and Search Next, this      ;
1397: EB0A         ; function can take an ambiguous file name and type as part of the          ;
1398: EB0A         ; File Control Block, but unlike those functions, the logical disk select   ;
1399: EB0A         ; code cannot be a"?". This function returns a directory code in A in the   ;
1400: EB0A         ; same way as the previous file operations.                                 ;
1401: EB0A         ;                                                                           ;
1402: EB0A         ;                                                                           ;
1403: EB0A         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 13H                                    ;
1404: EB0A         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1405: EB0A         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1406: EB0A         ;																			;
1407: EB0A         ;--------------------------------Delete File - 13 (19) ---------------------;
1408: EB0A             vDeleteFile:
1409: EB0A CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Reselect if needed
1410: EB0D CD 29 F2               CALL   CheckWrite           ; Terminate with error if Disk R/O
1411: EB10 0E 0C                  LD     C,fcbExtIndex        ; Load the extent number field
1412: EB12 CD F6 EF               CALL   SearchForDirectoryRecord ; Look for directory entry
1413: EB15
1414: EB15             DeleteFileLoop:
1415: EB15 CD 47 F1               CALL   AtEndOfDirectory     ; Have we worked thru all entries
1416: EB18 CA 22 F2               JP     Z,DirLocationToReturnLoc ; Return directory Index to caller
1417: EB1B
1418: EB1B         ; set each non zero disk map entry to 0 in the allocation vector
1419: EB1B CD 30 F2               CALL   CheckRODirectory     ; Terminate with error if File R/O
1420: EB1E CD 50 F1               CALL   GetCurrentDirectoryRecord ; Point to Directory Entry
1421: EB21 36 E5                  LD     (HL),emptyDir        ; Mark as Empty
1422: EB23 0E 00                  LD     C,FALSE              ; Set flag for remove
1423: EB25 CD 74 F1               CALL   ScanDiskMap          ; Reclaim Bisk Blocks, set to 0
1424: EB28 CD 69 F0               CALL   WriteDir             ; Update the directory
1425: EB2B CD 0B F0               CALL   GetNextDirectoryRecord ; Look for more
1426: EB2E C3 15 EB               JP     DeleteFileLoop       ; Loop
