1428: EB31         ;----------------------------Read Sequential - 14 (20) ---------------------;
1429: EB31         ;  This function reads the next record (l28-byte sector) from the designated;
1430: EB31         ; file into memory at the address set by the last Set DMA function call     ;
1431: EB31         ; (code 26, lAH). The record read is specified by the FCB's sequential      ;
1432: EB31         ; record field. This field is incremented by 1 so that a subsequent call    ;
1433: EB31         ; to Read Sequential will get the next record from the file. If the end of  ;
1434: EB31         ; the current extent is reached, then the BDOS will automatically open the  ;
1435: EB31         ; next extent and reset the sequential record field to 0, ready for the     ;
1436: EB31         ; next Read function call.                                                  ;
1437: EB31         ;  The file specified in the FCB must have been readied for input by        ;
1438: EB31         ; issuing an Open File (code 15, OFH) or a Create File (code 22, 16H)       ;
1439: EB31         ; BDOS call. The value OOH is returned in A to indicate a successful Read   ;
1440: EB31         ; Sequential operation, while a nonzero value shows that the Read could     ;
1441: EB31         ; not be completed because there was no data in the next record, as at the  ;
1442: EB31         ; end of file.                                                              ;
1443: EB31         ;                                                                           ;
1444: EB31         ;  Although it is not immediately obvious, you can change the sequential    ;
1445: EB31         ; record number, FCB$SEQREC, and within a given extent, read a record at    ;
1446: EB31         ; random. If you want to access any given record within a file, you must    ;
1447: EB31         ; compute which extent that record would be in and set the extent field in  ;
1448: EB31         ; the file control block (FCB$EXTENT) before you open the file. Thus,       ;
1449: EB31         ; although the function name implies sequential access, in practice you can ;
1450: EB31         ; use it to perform a simple type of random access. If you need to do true  ;
1451: EB31         ; random access, look ahead to the Random Read function (code 33), which    ;
1452: EB31         ; takes care of opening the correct extent automatically.                   ;
1453: EB31         ;  When you read data from a CP/M text file, the normal convention is to    ;
1454: EB31         ; fill the last record of the file with lAH characters (CONTROL-Z).         ;
1455: EB31         ; Therefore, two possible conditions can indicate end-of-file: either       ;
1456: EB31         ; encountering a IAH, or receiving a return code from the BDOS function     ;
1457: EB31         ; (in the A register) of OFFH. However, if the file that you are reading    ;
1458: EB31         ; is not an ASCII text file, then a IAH character has no special meaning,   ;
1459: EB31         ; it is just a normal data byte in the body of the file.	                ;
1460: EB31         ;                                                                           ;
1461: EB31         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 14H                                    ;
1462: EB31         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1463: EB31         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = 0  => Success							;
1464: EB31         ;								  <> 0  => No data read, Probably EOF		;
1465: EB31         ;																			;
1466: EB31         ;----------------------------Read Sequential - 14 (20) ---------------------;
1467: EB31             vReadSeq:
1468: EB31 CD 40 EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Reselect if needed
1469: EB34         ;ReadSeq:
1470: EB34 3E 01                  LD     A,SEQ_ACCESS
1471: EB36 32 AE F4               LD     (diskAccessType),A   ; Set flag as sequential Disk I/O
1472: EB39
1473: EB39             DiskRead:
1474: EB39 3E FF                  LD     A,TRUE
1475: EB3B 32 B2 F4               LD     (readModeFlag),A     ; Set Flag for read
1476: EB3E
1477: EB3E CD 6C EF               CALL   SetRecordVars        ; Set variables for current FCB
1478: EB41 3A BE F4               LD     A,(currentFileRecord)
1479: EB44 21 BC F4               LD     HL,fcbRecordCount
1480: EB47 BE                     CP     M                    ; is File Record < fcbRecordCount
1481: EB48 DA 5C EB               JP     C,RecordOK           ; skip if  yes
1482: EB4B         ; not enough records in the extent
1483: EB4B FE 80                  CP     RecordsPerExtent     ; Is record count the Max ?
1484: EB4D 20 22                  JR     NZ,NothingRead       ;  No, Exit with EOF
1485: EB4F
1486: EB4F CD A8 F2               CALL   OpenNextExt          ; Need to open the next extent
1487: EB52 AF                     XOR    A
1488: EB53 32 BE F4               LD     (currentFileRecord),A ; Reset the record count
1489: EB56 3A B6 EA               LD     A,(exitParameterByte) ; Was it a good Open
1490: EB59 B7                     OR     A
1491: EB5A 20 15                  JR     NZ,NothingRead       ;  exit if No
1492: EB5C
1493: EB5C             RecordOK:
1494: EB5C CD 58 F2               CALL   GetBlockNumber       ; Put it in absoluteCPMRecord
1495: EB5F CD 8A F2               CALL   WasBlockAllocated    ; Was it a good Allocation ?
1496: EB62 28 0D                  JR     Z,NothingRead        ; get out if not allocated
1497: EB64
1498: EB64 CD 90 F2               CALL   SetActualRecordAdd   ; Absolute CPM Record
1499: EB67 CD 7C F3               CALL   Seek                 ; Go to proper track,sector
1500: EB6A CD 15 EF               CALL   ReadBuffer           ; Read into DMA address
1501: EB6D CD 81 F0               CALL   UpdateRecordVariables ; update Record info
1502: EB70 C9                     RET
1503: EB71
1504: EB71             NothingRead:
1505: EB71 C3 2E F3               JP     SetExitParamTo1      ; No Data read
1506: EB74
1507: EB74         ;----------------------------Write Sequential - 15 (21) --------------------;
1508: EB74         ;	This function writes a record from the address specified in the last Set;
1509: EB74         ; DMA (code 26, lAH) function call to the file defined in the FCB. The      ;
1510: EB74         ; sequential record number in the FCB (RC) is updated by 1 so that          ;
1511: EB74         ; the next call to Write Sequential will write to the next record position  ;
1512: EB74         ; in the file. If necessary, a new extent will be opened to receive the new ;
1513: EB74         ; record.                                                                   ;
1514: EB74         ;  This function is directly analogous to the Read Sequential function,     ;
1515: EB74         ; writing instead of reading. The file specified in the FCB must first be   ;
1516: EB74         ; activated by an Open File (code 15,OFH) or create File call (code 22,16H).;
1517: EB74         ;  A directory code of OOH is returned in A to indicate that the Write was  ;
1518: EB74         ; successful, a nonzero value is returned if the Write could not be         ;
1519: EB74         ; completed because the disk was full.                                      ;
1520: EB74         ;                                                                           ;
1521: EB74         ;  As with the Read Sequential function (code 20, 14H), you can achieve     ;
1522: EB74         ; a simple form of random writing to the file by manipulating the           ;
1523: EB74         ; sequential record number (RC). However, you can only overwrite existing   ;
1524: EB74         ; records in the file, and if you want to move to another extent, you       ;
1525: EB74         ; must close the file and reopen it with the FCB$EXTENT field set to the    ;
1526: EB74         ; correct value.                                                            ;
1527: EB74         ;  The only logical error condition that can occur when writing to a file   ;
1528: EB74         ; is insufficient room on the disk to accommodate the next extent of the    ;
1529: EB74         ; file. Any hardware errors detected will be handled by the disk driver     ;
1530: EB74         ; built into the BIOS or BDOS.                                              ;
1531: EB74         ;                                                                           ;
1532: EB74         ;                                                                           ;
1533: EB74         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 15H                                    ;
1534: EB74         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1535: EB74         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = 0  => Success							;
1536: EB74         ;								  <> 0  => No data read, Probably EOF		;
1537: EB74         ;																			;
1538: EB74         ;----------------------------Write Sequential - 15 (21) --------------------;
1539: EB74
1540: EB74             vWriteSeq:
