1886: EC86         ;---------------------- Set File Attributes - 1E (30) ----------------------;
1887: EC86         ;  This function sets the bits that describe attributes of a file in the    ;
1888: EC86         ; relevant directory entries for the specified file. Each file can be       ;
1889: EC86         ; assigned up to 11 file attributes. Of these 11, two have predefined       ;
1890: EC86         ; meanings, four others are available for you to use, and the remaining     ;
1891: EC86         ; five are reserved for future use by CP/M.                                 ;
1892: EC86         ;  Each attribute consists of a single bit. The most significant bit of     ;
1893: EC86         ; each byte of the file name and type is used to store the attributes.      ;
1894: EC86         ; The file attributes are known by a code consisting of the letter "f"      ;
1895: EC86         ; (for file name) or "t" (for file type), followed by the number of the     ;
1896: EC86         ; character position and a single quotation mark. For example, the Read-Only;
1897: EC86         ; attribute is tl'.                                                         ;
1898: EC86         ;	The significance of the attributes is as follows:                       ;
1899: EC86         ;			fl' to f4' Available for you to use                             ;
1900: EC86         ;			f5' to fS' Reserved for future CP/M use                         ;
1901: EC86         ;			tl' Read-Only File attribute                                    ;
1902: EC86         ;			t2' System File attribute                                       ;
1903: EC86         ;			t3' Reserved for future CP/M use                                ;
1904: EC86         ;			                                                                ;
1905: EC86         ;  Attributes are set by presenting this function with an FCB in which the  ;
1906: EC86         ; unambiguous file name has been preset with the most significant bits      ;
1907: EC86         ; set appropriately. This function then searches the directory for a match  ;
1908: EC86         ; and changes the matched entries to contain the attributes which have been ;
1909: EC86         ; set in the FCB.                                                           ;
1910: EC86         ;  The BDOS will intercept any attempt to write on a file that has the      ;
1911: EC86         ; Read-Only attribute set. The DIR command in the CCP does not display any  ;
1912: EC86         ; file with System status.                                                  ;
1913: EC86         ;                                                                           ;
1914: EC86         ;  You can use the four attributes available to you to set up a file        ;
1915: EC86         ; security system, or perhaps to flag certain files that must be backed up  ;
1916: EC86         ; to other disks. The Search First and Search Next functions allow you to   ;
1917: EC86         ; view the complete file directory entry, so your programs can test the     ;
1918: EC86         ; attributes easily.                                                        ;
1919: EC86         ;                                                                           ;
1920: EC86         ;                                                                           ;
1921: EC86         ;			Function Code	:	C  = 1EH                                    ;
1922: EC86         ;			Entry Parameters:	DE = Address of File Control Block			;
1923: EC86         ;			Exit Parameters :	A  = Directory Code							;
1924: EC86         ;																			;
1925: EC86         ;---------------------- Set File Attributes - 1E (30) ----------------------;
