1957: ECA7         ;------------------------- Read Random - 21 (33) ---------------------------;
1958: ECA7         ; This function reads a specific CP/M record (128 bytes) from a random file ;
1959: ECA7         ; that is, a file in which records can be accessed directly. It assumes that;
1960: ECA7         ; you have already opened the file, set the DMA address using the BDOS      ;
1961: ECA7         ; Set DMA function, and set the specific record to be read into the random  ;
1962: ECA7         ; record number in the FCB. This function computes the extent of the        ;
1963: ECA7         ; specified record number and attempts to open it and read the correct CP/M ;
1964: ECA7         ; record into the DMA address.                                              ;
1965: ECA7         ;  The random record number in the FCB is three bytes long (at relative     ;
1966: ECA7         ; bytes 33, 34, and 35). Byte 33 is the least significant byte, 34 is the   ;
1967: ECA7         ; middle byte, and 35 the most significant. CP/M uses only the most         ;
1968: ECA7         ; significant byte (35) for computing the overall file size (function 35).  ;
1969: ECA7         ; You must set this byte to 0 when setting up the FCB. Bytes 33 and 34      ;
1970: ECA7         ; are used together for the Read Random, so you can access from record      ;
1971: ECA7         ; 0 to 65535 (a maximum file size of 8,388,480 bytes).                      ;
1972: ECA7         ;  This function returns with A set to 0 to indicate that the operation has ;
1973: ECA7         ; been completed successfully, or A set to a nonzero value if an error has  ;
1974: ECA7         ; occurred. The error codes are as follows:                                 ;
1975: ECA7         ;		A = 01 (attempt to read unwritten record)                           ;
1976: ECA7         ;		A = 03 (CP/M could not close current extent)                        ;
1977: ECA7         ;		A = 04 (attempt to read unwritten extent)                           ;
1978: ECA7         ;		A = 06 (attempt to read beyond end of disk)                         ;
1979: ECA7         ;		                                                                    ;
1980: ECA7         ;  Unlike the Read Sequential BOOS function (code 20, l4H), which updates   ;
1981: ECA7         ; the current (sequential) record number in the FCB, the Read Random        ;
1982: ECA7         ; function leaves the record number unchanged, so that a subsequent Write   ;
1983: ECA7         ; Random will replace the record just read.                                 ;
1984: ECA7         ;  You can follow a Read Random with a Write Sequential (code 21, l5H).     ;
1985: ECA7         ; This will rewrite the record just read, but will then update the          ;
1986: ECA7         ; sequential record number. Or you may choose to use a Read Sequential after;
1987: ECA7         ; the Read Random. In this case, the same record will be reread and the     ;
1988: ECA7         ; sequential record number will be incremented. In short, the file can be   ;
1989: ECA7         ; sequentially read or written once the Read Random has been used to        ;
1990: ECA7         ; position to the required place in the file.                               ;
1991: ECA7         ;                                                                           ;
1992: ECA7         ; To use the Read Random function, you must first open the base extent of   ;
1993: ECA7         ; the file, that is, extent O. Even though there may be no actual data      ;
1994: ECA7         ; records in this extent, opening permits the file to be processed          ;
1995: ECA7         ; correctly.                                                                ;
1996: ECA7         ;  One problem that is not immediately obvious with random files is that    ;
1997: ECA7         ; they can easily be created with gaps in the file. If you were to create   ;
1998: ECA7         ; the file with record number 0 and record number 5000, there would be no   ;
1999: ECA7         ; intervening file extents. Should you attempt to read or copy the file     ;
2000: ECA7         ; sequentially, even using CP/M's file copy utility, only the first extent  ;
2001: ECA7         ; (and in this case, record 0) would get copied. A Read Sequential function ;
2002: ECA7         ; would return an "end of file" error after reading record O. You must      ;
2003: ECA7         ; therefore be conscious of the type of the file that you try and read.     ;
2004: ECA7         ;                                                                           ;
2005: ECA7         ;                                                                           ;
2006: ECA7         ;                                                                           ;
2007: ECA7         ;			Function Code	:   C  = 21H                                    ;
2008: ECA7         ;			Entry Parameters:  DE = Address of File Control Block			;
2009: ECA7         ;			Exit Parameters :	A = 01 (attempt to read unwritten record)   ;
2010: ECA7         ;								A = 03 (CP/M could not close current extent);
2011: ECA7         ;								A = 04 (attempt to read unwritten extent)   ;
2012: ECA7         ;								A = 06 (attempt to read beyond end of disk) ;
2013: ECA7         ;																			;
2014: ECA7         ;------------------------- Read Random - 21 (33) ---------------------------;
2015: ECA7             vReadRandom:
